									Philip Migas on July 18, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            James,
Great article. Thank you for trying to help designers become better at their craft. I have used every point on your paper as criticism during at least one review at my design club. Here would by my additions:
‚Äì	A good game needs to do one thing really well. Any additional mechanics that don‚Äôt support the one main mechanic should probably be removed.
‚Äì	If you don‚Äôt have a prototype, you don‚Äôt have a game design. Don‚Äôt think about designing a game. Be active and put together a game prototype.
‚Äì	Don‚Äôt make a game that would be a better computer game. First person shooter board game are a good example. The board game will never be better than the digital version.
‚Äì	Don‚Äôt just make a player move several turns just to get to the important parts of the game. An example would be when a player needs to move several turns to a spot where they then draws a card. Usually best solution is to remove the board entirely. Apples to Apples is the best example of how this improved the game. Yes Apples to Apples (Oranges) had a board when it was first pitched to the publisher.
‚Äì	Have cards or dice, not both. Cards and dice are randomizers. You don‚Äôt need both.
‚Äì	The more control you can give a player during a random event the better. Try to let the players react to the random event. Don‚Äôt let the random event determine the success of the player.
‚Äì	Rules are made to be broken when you learn how to break the rule correctly. Most people don‚Äôt learn.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
