									Alex Churchill on July 24, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            A friend offers a few more fundamental tips along the same lines:
Decide the answer to the big three questions: What is this game about? What do the players do? Why is that more fun than doing something else? Decide what your game is about, then make it do that.
It‚Äôs not enough to have your mechanic be fun when it works; see what happens when it fails.
If you have different denominations of things, whether money or something else, then make them look different!
And more generally, the more different things are, the more different they should look. Different colours, plus consideration for colourblind players.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Lewis Pulsipher on July 24, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            I‚Äôve encountered many people, usually younger ones, who think that preferences don‚Äôt change, that people are just the same as they‚Äôve always been.  Yet the guideline about losing a turn highlights a change in attitudes.  40 years ago, losing a turn occasionally was expected, it was part of the strategy, now it‚Äôs anathema.  I think this may show how much games today have become more about doing than about thinking (video games being the obvious example).  You can think while you‚Äôve lost a turn, but you can‚Äôt do.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Tom Jolly on July 24, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            Excellent list; it sums up pretty much everything I‚Äôve ever learned about game design. One thing I might add to it (which you sort-of covered) is, when given a choice of losing things and gaining things in your design, always select ‚Äúgaining‚Äù. Players always have a sense of accomplishment while gaining stuff, and dissatisfaction while losing stuff. I discovered this while designing Drakon, where the original object was to discard all your tiles in hand, versus gaining gold coins as you moved around. Totally changed the feel of the game without substantially affecting the mechanics or play.
There are likely exceptions to every rule here, but they are fairly unique (for example, killing players off early vs Werewolves of Miller‚Äôs Hollow and its ilk), but overall, this is a very solid set of design rules. Thanks for posting!

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
